Yes, that is a perfect solution!

If you enable Row Level Security (RLS) but add a policy that allows **read and write access to "public" (anon)**, the integration will work perfectly without needing a login screen.

You can run this SQL in your Supabase SQL Editor to set that up:

```sql
-- 1. Enable RLS (if not already enabled)
alter table master_profiles enable row level security;
alter table job_applications enable row level security;

-- 2. Create "Allow All" policies for the anonymous key
create policy "Public Access" on master_profiles for all using (true) with check (true);
create policy "Public Access" on job_applications for all using (true) with check (true);
```

This effectively tells Supabase: "Security is 'on', but the rule is that anyone with the API Key can do anything."

I have also made a small update to the **Supabase Service** to make it more robust. I switched the sorting logic to use the `id` column instead of `created_at`. This prevents errors if your database table columns are named slightly differently (e.g., `updated_at` vs `created_at`), as the `id` is guaranteed to exist and be sequential.

